VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cigarette. The dog is useless. Here\'s another example of adding something into the video that isn\'t even there in the first place. This is a shot of our surveillance camera outside of our house. And I thought I\'d have some fun with that. So, through the surveillance'

[06:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'camera, we see Bigfoot approaching the front door and knocking. I have a ton of examples of these, but I\'m just going to show you a couple of them because I think they are hilarious. Got a package which disappears in that example.'

[06:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Here he is running around the corner with a package which he drops very carelessly and it looks like he\'s saying something nasty into the camera. I don\'t know why he\'s got this job he hates so much. In this case, the starting image was just a picture of our kitten Ellie'

[07:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'laying on the floor and I just wanted to try a simple morph. Morph into a lion. I did several generations and this is the best one I got. We have sort of an extra leg thing happening here for a second, but I think if I kept at it, I\'d'

[07:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'probably get a generation I like. But again, this is without a start or end frame. If I had done another version of the picture where I\'d already had the lion head there, it probably would have been a much smoother transition and the AI wouldn\'t have had the need to create a third leg or whatever.'

[07:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I started with this image which I did create in Reeve and the old woman work at the cash register as jars of olives move down the conveyor belt. And here she is working at the cash register as olives move down the conveyor belt.'

[07:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In fairness, I also got this generation where her nose just falls right off right at the beginning of the video. I didn\'t prompt for that and I\'m not sure why it happened. Now here\'s one that normally would be a great candidate for a start and end'

[08:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frame. If I want the car to go down the road, I\'d have two pictures, one where it\'s here, one where it\'s down at the end of the road, but I wanted to see what would happen if I didn\'t have an end frame. Futuristic car suddenly starts, revs, and drives toward the horizon at high speed leaving tread'

[08:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'marks. Now I do want you to take notice that this was actually the Vedu 2.0 model that I ran this on by accident, but I got the result I wanted, so I was happy with that. So this is just a reminder to not totally discount the older models. Sometimes you can get'

[08:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'great results from them like I did here. It\'s not the same resolution as the Q1 model, but I like the final result. Although I did not get the tread marks that I wanted, but I did not need an end frame and I still got what I was looking for.'

[08:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And that\'s the older model. Okay, let\'s talk about start and end frames. I\'m going to show you examples from the version two model and the Q1 model. They both get great results and they\'re both worth trying in some situations. One of the uses for start'

[08:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and end frames to be able to create a longer video where instead of 5 seconds, you could make it 10 or 30 or however long you wanted to by taking the last frame of one video and making it the first or start frame of the second video and so on, so you can string them'

[09:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'together. So what you need to do that is a series of images that make sense and tell the story. And that\'s what was great about using Reeve over here to do this is because I can create one image say of Einstein and Elmo and then say what would I like to change and I could'

[09:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just say I want Elmo on his shoulder. I want there to be this in the background. So I was able to make this whole series of images where Einstein and Elmo are walking down the street and then Elmo throws up cotton candy and pizza and then just one at a time I used a start'

[09:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and end frame and then chain them together exactly as I was talking about. And then I ran it through some sound effects generation and added some music and we end up with something like this. Keep in mind it\'s the 2.0 model, so it\'s not as high resolution. You can see the transitions as they move'

[09:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from one segment to the other if you\'re looking closely. But you probably understand the concept of what we\'re doing here. Did the exact same thing with this'

[09:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'series here with Gordon Ramsay and Oprah in a telephone booth as Bigfoot comes up, so it tells the whole story of them in the rain and you know having some intimate moments and then being interrupted by Bigfoot. String that all together, add music and sound effects. So you\'ll see some movement in the'

[10:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'background because the images aren\'t exactly the same angle and the exactly the same background, so it\'s not perfect in this way. If you really wanted to get down to you could edit these images so that there\'s consistency in the background. This was more of a proof of concept, which I think worked pretty'

[10:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'well despite the sort of changes and morphing that happened because the images are so inherently different from one another. We\'re going to go back to this woman with the large nose working in a grocery store and I wanted to try some start and end frames even though they were basically different ladies.'

[10:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This was the start frame and then this was the end frame. And the story I was trying to tell, an old woman with very long nose working at the cash register as a kitten moves toward her on the conveyor belt. And this time I am using the Q1 model. This was one of the better'

[11:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ones I got given how different the women actually were, we got more of a smooth transition where the nose sort of shrinks and the hair changes color rather than an extreme cut, which is what I was afraid was going to happen and did in some cases. Here\'s another'

[11:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'example with similar results. We do have a good bit of tearing when we\'ve got this morphing here, but that\'s just because the images are so completely different. It probably would have made more sense if it was a jump cut, but that\'s not what I wanted here. I wanted'

[11:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to see how this would morph, which it did an okay job and probably just better starting images and ending images with the result in mind, would have turned much better. Okay, this next example blew my mind because I thought there\'s no way it\'s going to do exactly what it'

[11:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'did. So, remember this starting image here with the woman with the cigarette catching the sun\'s hair on fire, and then the second image is her trying to spray the fire out. Now, this is a huge difference in images. She\'s in a'

[11:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'completely different place. You would absolutely expect a jump cut. But, here\'s one example. She actually moves around the camera shifts, the boy turns, the dog moves. We\'ve got a second dog in here, but the first dog doesn\'t vanish.'

[12:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It moves over behind the people, and everything stays consistent. Now, he does change his face a little bit, but it\'s a different picture. The fact that it didn\'t do a jump cut here, and that it actually tried to maintain the movement, is absolutely incredible. And here\'s another example where the exact'

[12:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'same thing happened. These were the first two attempts I made. I didn\'t cut out any jump cut versions. It did exactly what I wanted to both times. I\'ve never, in any platform, seen a start and end frame process that could'

[12:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'come anywhere near bringing two completely different images like that together in a seamless way. But, these examples are from the 2.0 model, which I did before the Q1 was out. But, this is a typical use case for start and end'

[12:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frames. When you have two slightly different pictures of a model, and you want to have some movement between the two. In this case, there was some pretty extreme changes in clothing and background, but it still did a pretty good job. And this is the older version of bringing those two images together.'

[12:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This one here where she starts back there, and then another image where she\'s closer to the camera, and the face does change a little bit, but we\'ve got that movement that we want. And so, here\'s another example where she starts way back in the back, and then I just'

[13:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generated a slightly different version, and it compensated for the change in background by having her move naturally over there. Now, I could keep going with examples, but I invite you to just come to the site and look at some of the other examples that people are doing.'

[13:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, I want to step back to the version 2.0 of the model to show you what they\'re doing with reference images. This isn\'t a brand new feature, but they have recently added the ability to add up to seven reference images to use in your video. Let me show you how this'

[13:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'works. In the reference to video section, you have your basic prompt section. You\'re going to choose your model up here. We\'re going to go with Bedu 2.0. You have your normal range of options here. If you\'re going for quality, I would stay away from speed.'

[13:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It is fast, but it\'s not the highest quality. I would go at least 720p and play with these movement amplitudes just like you did in all the other generations. The difference here is that you can specify specific people, objects, characters, places that you can'

[13:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use over and over again by referencing images. Now, you have two sections here. You have images where you can add images on the fly while you\'re creating, and then you have my references, which are basically the same thing except that you\'ve created a library of references'

[14:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that you use on a regular basis. For example, my studio, my face, Tracy, Tess, and so on. So, if I found myself using something on a regular basis, I could just click the plus sign here. Right now, I just use this one image of'

[14:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Presley, but I could do several more with different angles to give it a little bit more information. Give it a reference name, Presley, and click on next step. You\'ll confirm this information here, and now Presley is available as a character. So, I can just click her or several others. If I wanted'

[14:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to combine me and Presley in a picture, I would choose both of us. And let\'s say I wanted us in the studio, so I would choose that as well. When I click on done, we have these three images here, and we have our names. What I really'

