VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'combined them beautifully. Although that\'s not a 100% accurate representation of my face, this was the reference model that was just used with one image and not several. Look, we\'ve already got our results with Presley and me in the studio. Got four different ones to choose from,'

[15:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'coffee steaming and everything. So here we used an image reference of Flurb, we had a field, and we put Tess on his back. And here we just put a random old woman on Flurb\'s back. You\'ll notice he\'s wearing a Bob Doyle Media shirt as was the original image character.'

[15:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Here we only used the one reference image, and the prompt was handheld camera close-up of Tess scuba diving deep underwater, and we got what I think are a couple of really nice examples. Beautiful colors, good movement. Here\'s'

[15:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'another one. Same prompt. One reference image. Here you\'ll see that the reference image was just this image of this creature, which we combined with the prompt, the image snuggles close to a grandmotherly old'

[16:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'woman on an old couch, and then we get something a little like this. But one of the more interesting uses of this reference feature is if you have a product, and you\'d like a spokesperson'

[16:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to interact with this product in these videos any one consistency between the videos because it\'s your product and it needs to stay that way. So I created all of these fictitious cereals, Godios, Poopoes, Uh-ohs,'

[16:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which resulted in a lot of generations like this where I was combining my picture with the box, Tess with the boxes, this guy here with the boxes, and even though this isn\'t at the resolution of the Q1 model that I\'m certainly'

[16:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'expecting that they will add this functionality to that model eventually. Using these types of videos as a base and then adding lip sync, you could literally create a commercial for a product with custom characters who look and sound however you want and can be'

[17:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'virtual spokespeople for this product called Uh-ohs. Or here\'s Bob Doyle for Godios. Now let\'s take a look at the template feature. I know you\'ve probably seen effects like this all over the place, but let\'s just take a look at a couple'

[17:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of examples of these. This is the Nap Me template where you just upload an image. In this case, a picture of this girl just standing here and then the Nap Me filter gives it this result. Here\'s another example. Falling asleep in the vision department'

[17:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it even works with kitty cats. You\'ve got the balloon me template, the fly me template, the tiny me template. Why, you can even turn your cat into a mech or a bee if you prefer, but I kind'

[17:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of think that\'s been done. So now let\'s look at sound effects. Several platforms have added the ability to add sound to videos after the effect. Most of them are using MM audio or something similar that looks at the'

[17:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video and does its best to put the appropriate sound effects in the appropriate places. Sometimes it\'s great, sometimes it\'s just hilariously bad. I\'ve always enjoyed it, but this gives us a different level of control. So remember this video here? This is'

[18:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just screaming for some sound. Now this is an 8-second video, so we\'ve got 8 seconds of audio that we can play with here. As soon as I click in this AI sound effects area, you\'re going to see this pop up. 0 seconds to 5 seconds.'

[18:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This can be changed, but this allows you to say how long of a duration this particular sound effect you\'re about to prompt will last. For this video, let\'s say I want the engine to be revving right at the very beginning and then it'

[18:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'takes off down the road. This is just one example, but let\'s say so from 0 to maybe 2 seconds. So at the beginning we want the car engine revving. So I\'m going to write car engine revving and I actually want that to go'

[18:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for maybe the first 2 seconds. So I\'m going to adjust the length of that particular clip down to 2 seconds and then on the next line, process starts over again. Let\'s see what happens if at the 2-second mark I say that the car is'

[18:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to take off down the highway. Car takes off down the highway toward the horizon. Maybe it\'ll fade out and that would be for the duration of the rest of the clip. So I\'m going to move this all'

[19:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the way over to the 8-second mark, but I would just want this to start at 2 seconds. Now we may need to adjust this based on my experiments, but I wanted to show you what happens when we do this. And just for fun, let\'s just put in another sound effect, a random sound'

[19:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'effect of something that we may not even be able to see, like people cheering. So, let\'s say audience cheering, and we\'ll start that at let\'s say that\'ll be at the end, and we\'ll start that maybe at 7 seconds,'

[19:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'okay? So, now we got three different sound effects coming in at basically three different times, and let\'s just create that and see what we end up with. Okay, so we had the car revving at the'

[19:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'beginning, we had it taking off down the highway, and at 7 seconds, we had the cheering. At this point in development to put that sound with the video requires that you download the audio file and the video file, and you edit them together in an editor. But, this is about the simplest editing you can get.'

[20:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We\'ll download that file, we\'ve already got the video file. You should be able to use virtually any video editor for this. I don\'t even know why I\'m showing you, this is so simple. But, we bring the video clip, and we just line them up on the timeline together. Now, I\'m noticing here that the sound effect I'

[20:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generated is longer than the video clip. Let me go back and check what I was doing. The mistake I made was not adjusting the total duration, which should be based on the video clip itself. So, that was 8 seconds, so I need to move all this down. I\'m just going to change the timeline a little'

[20:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bit so that the audience comes in at maybe 5 seconds instead, and now it will end at the same time as the video. So, let me recreate that. We\'ll download that clip, we will put it in the editor here, and replace this clip with the correct one.'

[20:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, that to me is awesome. You don\'t need to pay for a sound effects library, you can just generate it and put it'

[20:51] [scene:talk]
